The paper discusses the challenge of creating Intelligent Agents (IAs) to assist medical service providers (MSPs) and consumers in establishing a more personalized human-to-human dialogue. This involves considering socially-relevant information about how a diagnosis should be communicated and discussed with the patient. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, as well as the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the need for trust and commitment in the outcome of the interaction, which could fall under the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a conceptual framework for personalized social interactions, which could also fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
